gauthier@ug.cs.dal.ca (Paul Gauthier) writes:

>Is there an archive on the net of _real_ random numbers. Not pseudo-random,
>computer generated numbers, but numbers collected from some real-world random
>events (like a lottery draw, or somesuch). Surely someone, somewhere has
>collected a sizable database of such information for cryptographic or
>compression-related purposes?

Dear Real_Random_Number_Fans,

Yes, 

the Real Random Number Generator exists!
========================================

His name is PURAN II (Physical Uniform Random Number generator).

PURANII has been developed at University of Aachen (Germany).
In my PhD thesis, I designed this new random number generator
based on thermal noise of a semiconductor diode. 

Technical Aspects of PURAN II :
 
  - Bandwith of noise:       0 .. 1.5 GHz
  - sampling rate:           200 KHz
  - sampling circuit:        GaAs flip-flops
  - data transfer between 
    generator and computer:  fiberglas optics
  - statistical analysing:   on board with programmable gatearrays (XILINK)
  - first storage:           Giga-Tape (2 GByte) with parityinformation

  - correlation coefficient
    first order of bits:     < 10^(-8)

-> 110100100100100100100111110 <- a very small example ;-)

Available:
  
  - Via Giga-Tape 2 Gbyte , Cartridges (QIC150, QIC24, QIC11) or other tapes
  - Will be available on ftp (10 MB): 137.226.4.105 in april 1992
  - Will be available on CD ( 600 MB ) in april 1992
  
Software necessary to use the random bits in C++, C and for those incorrigible 
Pascal (Turbo) will also be available on ftp.

I am offering the tapes for the cost of copying and shipping.

If you are interested, connect me via email:

                ri@dfv.rwth-aachen.de

